# ovh_vps_vnc (Resource)

Opens a VNC console session on an OVHcloud VPS by calling
`POST /vps/{serviceName}/openConsoleAccess` and exposes the resulting
host / port / password in Terraform state.

~> **WARNING** The credentials returned by OVHcloud are **one-shot**:
the API issues a fresh session intended for immediate use, with no
companion GET endpoint and no explicit close call. This resource
therefore:

* Stores the credentials in state once at create time.
* Has a no-op Read (the values are treated as opaque after creation).
* Has a no-op Delete (the session auto-expires server-side); destroying
  the resource simply drops it from state.
* Forces replacement on any change to `service_name` or `protocol`,
  which re-issues fresh credentials via a new POST.

Because the password is stored in Terraform state, ensure your state
backend is encrypted.

## Example Usage

```hcl
resource "ovh_vps_vnc" "session" {
  service_name = "vps-xxxxxx.vps.ovh.net"
  protocol     = "VNC"
}

output "vnc_endpoint" {
  value = "${ovh_vps_vnc.session.host}:${ovh_vps_vnc.session.port}"
}

output "vnc_password" {
  value     = ovh_vps_vnc.session.password
  sensitive = true
}
```

## Argument Reference

* `service_name` - (Required, ForceNew) The service_name of your VPS.
* `protocol` - (Required, ForceNew) The VNC protocol to open. One of
  `VNC` or `VNCOverWebSocket`.

## Attributes Reference

* `id` - Composed as `<service_name>/<protocol>`.
* `host` - VNC host to connect to.
* `port` - VNC TCP port to connect to.
* `password` - One-shot VNC password. Sensitive.
